Answers

Question 1

For most payment options, it costs extra to travel more than 30 minutes on a bike.

  1. Find the number of trips with more than 30 minutes long. But dont just use the duration variable!
MoreThirty <- 
Trips %>%
  mutate(startTime = hour(sdate) + minute(sdate)/60, endTime = hour(edate) + minute(edate)/60) %>% # calculate the start and end time in decimal form
  mutate(total = endTime-startTime) %>% # find the total duration of the trip in decimal form 
  filter(total > .5) # find where the duration is greater than 30 min (so, 0.5 in decimal form)
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.3.3
dim(MoreThirty)
## [1] 40325    10
(nrow(MoreThirty) / nrow(Trips)) * 100 # finding the percent of total trips that are over 30 minutes 
## [1] 6.168137
  1. Map the end stations. Use this to start:
MapEndStation <- 
  MoreThirty %>%
  group_by(estation) %>% # we want our new 
  summarize(rides = n()) %>%
  left_join(Stations, by = c("estation" = "name"))

dim(MapEndStation)
## [1] 336   6

Question 2

I actually use the DC bikeshare quite a bit. The stations I use the most are 13th St & New York Ave NW MLK Library/9th & G St NW, and Columbia Rd & Georgia Ave NW. In 2014, I was a casual rider.

  1. Find how many other casual riders there were at those stations.
casual_favoriteStations <- Trips %>% 
  filter(sstation %in% c('13th St & New York Ave NW', 'MLK Library/9th & G St NW', 'Columbia Rd & Georgia Ave NW')) %>% # filter out the stations we want
  filter(client == "Casual") %>% # get just the casual riders (this can be written as just one filter statement)
  group_by(sstation) %>% 
  summarise(riders = n()) # total number of riders at the station over the time period

head(casual_favoriteStations)
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##                       sstation riders
##                          <chr>  <int>
## 1    13th St & New York Ave NW    439
## 2 Columbia Rd & Georgia Ave NW     87
## 3    MLK Library/9th & G St NW    290
  1. On what days of the year were there the most casual riders?
casual_popularDays <- Trips %>% 
  filter(sstation %in% c('13th St & New York Ave NW', 'MLK Library/9th & G St NW', 'Columbia Rd & Georgia Ave NW')) %>% # filter out the stations we want
  filter(client == "Casual") %>% 
  mutate(date = as_date(sdate)) %>% # create a date 
  group_by(sstation, date) %>% # we want to group by days and stations because that becomes our case in the new table 
  summarize(riders = n()) # total number of riders on a day at a station

head(casual_popularDays)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
## # Groups:   sstation [1]
##                    sstation       date riders
##                       <chr>     <date>  <int>
## 1 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-01      5
## 2 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-02     10
## 3 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-03     16
## 4 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-04     13
## 5 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-05     19
## 6 13th St & New York Ave NW 2014-10-06      8
  1. Which station has the lowest percent of its ridership in the casual category?
highestType <-  Trips %>% 
  filter(sstation %in% c('13th St & New York Ave NW', 'MLK Library/9th & G St NW', 'Columbia Rd & Georgia Ave NW')) %>% # filter out the stations we want
  group_by(sstation) %>% # per station
  summarize(casual = sum(client == "Casual"), reg = sum(client == "Registered")) %>% # total clients of each type
  mutate(percentReg = reg / (casual + reg), percentCasual = casual / (casual + reg))  # percent of each client type

Question 3

  1. Metro Center / 12th & G St NW is a very popular station for people who bike to work. What are the most common end stations for people who start there?
metroCenter <- Trips %>%
  filter(sstation == "Metro Center / 12th & G St NW") %>% # we only want trips that start at Metro Center
  group_by(estation) %>% # group the end stations 
  summarize(trips = n()) %>% # n() counts the number of observations in a group
  arrange(desc(trips)) # greatest to least trips

head(metroCenter)
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##                        estation trips
##                           <chr> <int>
## 1 5th St & Massachusetts Ave NW   186
## 2                 5th & K St NW   156
## 3    14th & Rhode Island Ave NW   119
## 4 Metro Center / 12th & G St NW   103
## 5                 8th & H St NW    97
## 6                 1st & M St NE    94
  1. What about people who start at Smithsonian / Jefferson Dr & 12th St SW? This station is probably a lot of tourists! (Hint: redo (a) to include both of these start points)
smithsonianAndMC <- Trips %>%
  filter(sstation %in% c("Smithsonian / Jefferson Dr & 12th St SW", "Metro Center / 12th & G St NW")) %>% # we only want trips that start at Smithsonian/Jefferson
  group_by(sstation, estation) %>% # group the end stations and start stations
  summarize(trips = n()) %>% # n() counts the number of observations in a group
  arrange(desc(trips)) # greatest to least trips

head(smithsonianAndMC)
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
## # Groups:   sstation [2]

## 3 Smithsonian / Jefferson Dr & 12th St SW
## 4 Smithsonian / Jefferson Dr & 12th St SW
## 5           Metro Center / 12th & G St NW
## 6           Metro Center / 12th & G St NW

  1. Map both of these patterns.
# this question is pretty vague. I chose to just map the raw number of trips for each starting station. With more time I would map percentages instead. 

smithsonianAndMC_withLocation <- smithsonianAndMC %>%
  left_join(Stations, by = c("estation" = "name")) # join by end station to get its location data

myMap <- get_map(location="Logan Circle",source="google",maptype="roadmap",zoom=13)
## Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=Logan+Circle&zoom=13&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=roadmap&language=en-EN&sensor=false
## Information from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Logan%20Circle&sensor=false
ggmap(myMap) + geom_point(data = smithsonianAndMC_withLocation, aes(x = long, y = lat, color = sstation, size = trips), alpha = 0.6)
